= Pediatric ME/CFS: School-Attending and Ambulatory Cases
<ch:pediatric-ambulatory>

Children and adolescents with mild to moderate ME/CFS who retain capacity for school attendance—even partial attendance—represent a critical population for early intervention. The substantially better prognosis in pediatric ME/CFS (54–94% improvement or recovery versus $lt.eq$22% in adults) creates both opportunity and urgency: appropriate early management may preserve the window for recovery, while inappropriate management (particularly graded exercise therapy) risks progression to severe, potentially irreversible disease @Rowe2017pediatric @CDC2024pediatric.

This chapter addresses ambulatory pediatric patients who can attend school at least part-time. For children who are housebound or bedbound, see Chapter @ch:pediatric-severe. For adult mild-moderate management, see Chapter @ch:action-mild-moderate.
